1️⃣ Pair Sum (Two Pointers)
🔹 Problem

Given a sorted array, check if any pair sums to a target.

🧠 Python Code (5 lines)
a=[1,2,4,7]; t=9
l,r=0,len(a)-1
while l<r:
    if a[l]+a[r]==t: print(True); break
    elif a[l]+a[r]<t: l+=1
    else: r-=1

🖥️ Output
True

📖 Explanation

We place one pointer at the start (l) and one at the end (r).

If the sum is:

Equal to target → pair found

Smaller → move left pointer right

Larger → move right pointer left

This works because the array is sorted.

⏱️ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(1)

🎤 Interview Explanation

“I used two pointers from both ends to reduce the time complexity from O(n²) to O(n).”

2️⃣ Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array
🔹 Problem

Remove duplicates from a sorted array and print unique elements.

🧠 Python Code (4 lines)
a=[1,1,2,2,3]
u=[a[0]]
for x in a[1:]:
    if x!=u[-1]: u.append(x)
print(u)

🖥️ Output
[1, 2, 3]

📖 Explanation

Since the array is sorted, duplicates are next to each other.

We compare the current element with the last stored unique element.

If different → add it.

⏱️ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n) (can be optimized to O(1) in-place)

🎤 Interview Explanation

“I compare adjacent elements using pointers to remove duplicates in one pass.”

🎤 FAANG Interview Round (Professional Answers)

Q1. What is the two-pointer technique?
A: A technique where two indices traverse the array from different directions to optimize time complexity.

Q2. When can we use two pointers?
A: Mostly with sorted arrays or problems involving pairs.

Q3. Why is it better than brute force?
A: It reduces nested loops and improves efficiency.

Q4. Can two pointers work on unsorted arrays?
A: Usually no, unless combined with sorting or hashing.

